Yippie!  My battle versus the PC may actually be over, or at least, I think I isolated the problem.  It's one of the following three things:  a) my primary HDD was or is going bad, b) Windows Vista is now incompatible with iTunes, or c) I have no clue but now it works.  Anyway, my PC went through a whole 24 hours without crashing or BSoD'ing ... so yay!  I'm currently tagging and getting Seasons Four and Five ready for upload, but here is the third season.  I warn those of you who haven't seen this show before, Season Three is definitely where the show starts taking on a much darker shade of humor.  Danger is afoot in the new incorporated town of Majestic.

If you've never sat down and watched Weeds, you're missing out ... this is probably one of the funniest shows on Television today.  As the description above tells you, it's about a suburban single-mom who has absolutely no job skills and because her husband was up to his eyeballs in debt when he suddenly dropped dead, she chooses to become the biggest pot-dealer in her small SoCal town of Agrestic.  Comedy and drama ensue as Nancy's life and that of her family only complicate matters.  Personally, I can always count on this show to lift my spirits.  And the show actually gets even funnier if you're a little baked.  Enjoy!


Tradition, tradition ... uh, here are a few little &quot;trivia&quot; tidbits I know:
1.  Two of the regulars on the show actually worked together before the show started, though they didn't actually meet in person until the first cast read-through on the pilot.  Alexander Gould (Shane) voiced the title character in Finding Nemo, the little-finned fish, Nemo.  Elizabeth Perkins (Celia) voiced Nemo's mother Coral.  Since the film was animated and most of the cast did their voices in private sound-booth recordings, the two never met.  In a spooky-odd sort of way, Nemo and Coral never met either, in the beginning of the film, Coral is killed by an eel while Nemo is just a fertile egg ... spooky-weird.
2. While &quot;Agrestic&quot; means fields, country, or rural, it is also oddly enough an anagram for &quot;Cigarets&quot;.

